f7f1823c-e271-490b-8b4a-4d16e73c2d38	https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/crc-1233-robust-vision	CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" - BCCN Tübingen	{"CRC 1233 \\"Robust Vision\\"","Topics, aims and projects","Aim 1a: Generative and causal modeling","Aim 1b: Feedback and neural representations","Aim 2: Dynamic input","Aim 3: Precortical image transformations",Central,"About us",Contact}	CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" - BCCN Tübingen Research CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" MICrONS Neurorobotics ITN "SwitchBoard" BMBF funding (2010-2017) Education Master of Science "Neural Information Processing" Doctoral Program SMARTSTART Faculty Network Timeline Past events Research CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" MICrONS Neurorobotics ITN "SwitchBoard" BMBF funding (2010-2017) Education Master of Science "Neural Information Processing" Doctoral Program SMARTSTART Faculty Network Timeline Past events CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" The collaborative research center “Robust Vision – Inference Principles and Neural Mechanisms” ( CRC 1233 ) deals with basic principles of biological and machine vision, and is a close collaboration between scientists from the University and the Max Planck Institute for Intelligent Systems. Human visual perception is amazingly robust: Even in highly variable environments, we are able to make reliable inferences about the spatial arrangement of the world from limited visual information. To achieve this, our brain must perform complex computations. Artificial vision systems, in turn – as used, for example, in self-driving cars – are making steep progress in reproducing the visual skills of humans. The goal of this joint initiative will be to better understand the principles and algorithms that enable robust visual inference both in humans and machines. Topics, aims and projects Aim 1a: Generative and causal modeling Project 1: Physics-based scene understanding ( Gehler , Lensch ), ended with 1st funding period Project 2: Robust material inference ( Lensch ) Project 3: Comparing humans and machines on robust visual inference (Wallis, Bethge ), ended with 1st funding period Project 4: Causal inference strategies in human vision ( Wichmann , Bethge , Schölkopf ) Project 17: Learning explainable policies for self-driving cars from little data ( Akata , Geiger ) Aim 1b: Feedback and neural representations Project 5: Task–dependend top down modulation of visual processing ( von Luxburg , Franz , Dayan ) Project 6: Top-down control of visual inference in sensory representations in early visual cortex ( Macke , Sinz ) Project 7: Large-scale neuronal interactions during natural vision ( Siegel , Bartels ) Project 8: Integration of bottom-up and top-down processing in perceptual learning during sleep ( Rauss , Nienborg ), ended with 1st funding period Aim 2: Dynamic input Project 9: Natural dynamic scene processing in the human brain ( Bartels , Black ) Project 10: Natural stimuli for mice: environment statistics and neural representations in the early visual system ( Busse , Euler ) Project 11: Stable vision in the presence of fixational eye movements: where and how is the retinal image perceptually stabilized? ( Hafed , Franke ) Transferproject: Physiologically inspired robust electro-optical autofocals ( Wahl , Rifai) Aim 3: Precortical image transformations Project 12: Image processing within a locally complete retinal ganglion cell population ( Euler , Bethge ) Project 13: Visual processing of feedforward and feedback signals in the dLGN ( Busse , Berens ) Project 14: Image-processing computations in artificial vision ( Stingl , Zeck , Schwarz ) Central Information structure project: A collaborative data management platform for reproducible neuroscience and machine learning ( Sinz , Berens ) While the two images on the right show exactly the same scene, the pixel values on the left are very different due to the differences in lighting. For humans, this can be easily seen, but for artificial algorithms this is a challenging task. In the CRC, we study commonalities and differences between natural and artificial vision systems to find out the principles underlying robust visual processing. About us At the Bernstein Center Tübingen, scientists from various disciplines, including theoretical and experimental neurobiology, machine learning, and medicine, collaborate in order to analyze the basis of inference processes in the brain. In particular, a main research goal is to understand the coordinated interaction of neurons during information processing. Contact office@bccn-tuebingen.de Bernstein Center for Computational Neuroscience Tübingen Imprint Privacy	{neuroscience,scientists,neurobiology,university,neurorobotics,faculty,tübingen,physics,science,medicine,transferproject,geiger,research,tuebingen,luxburg,franz,master,gehler,max,bernstein,office,nienborg,autofocals,timeline,wichmann,disciplines,neurons,cortex,1a,electro,ganglion,funding,cell,mice,education,siegel,institute,brain,busse,switchboard,deals,dayan,franke,feedforward,statistics,computations,von,bethge,modulation,goal,berens,projects,integration,transformations,collaboration,events,machine,cars}	2024-07-14 16:12:17.418673	{https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/crc-1233-robust-vision,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/microns,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/neurorobotics,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/itn-switchboard,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/bmbf-funding-2010-2017,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/education,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/education/master-of-science-neural-information-processing,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/education/doctoral-program,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/education/smartstart,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/faculty,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/network,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/timeline,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/timeline/past-events,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/crc-1233-robust-vision,ht