e383b929-0d47-42e3-87ef-c70e1f8a033e	https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/microns	MICrONS - BCCN Tübingen	{"Machine Intelligence From Cortical Networks (MICrONS)","About us",Contact}	MICrONS - BCCN Tübingen Research CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" MICrONS Neurorobotics ITN "SwitchBoard" BMBF funding (2010-2017) Education Master of Science "Neural Information Processing" Doctoral Program SMARTSTART Faculty Network Timeline Past events Research CRC 1233 "Robust Vision" MICrONS Neurorobotics ITN "SwitchBoard" BMBF funding (2010-2017) Education Master of Science "Neural Information Processing" Doctoral Program SMARTSTART Faculty Network Timeline Past events Machine Intelligence From Cortical Networks (MICrONS) Although neuroscience has inspired many elements of artificial neuronal networks, the mammalian visual system is still markedly different from current state-of-the-art deep neural networks in terms of its circuit architecture, robustness , and ability to learn. Two groups at the Bernstein center (Bethge, Sinz) are part of a multi-university consortium funded by the MICrONs program within the Obama BRAINinitiative, that is setting out to narrow the gap between current state-of-the-art deep learning and algorithms of the mammalian visual system by exploring circuit level functional and anatomical patterns of populations of cortical neurons. The approach is guided by data collected from cortical networks across three hierarchically organized visual areas in a behaving mouse at an unprecedented scale and detail. Using two- and three-photon imaging the team is collecting the distributed patterns of neural activity in response to artificial and natural stimuli from nearly all ~100,000 neurons in 1mm 3 of cortex in vivo . The functional imaging is followed by dense electron-microscopy reconstruction of the connectome in the same tissue. Using this historic dataset, the team aims at a full characterization of the functional properties, morphology, and connectivity of all neurons in all six layers across three interconnected areas of the mammalian cortex, and the computations they implement. Left: Stack of recording planes in visual cortex. Middle Top: Six somas of pyramidal cells contacted by one axon of an inhibitory interneuron. Middle bottom: 320 functionally recorded postsynaptic targets. Right top: 5000 of about 200 000 presynaptic axons. Right bottom: 111 functionally recorded postsynaptic target with significant orientation tuning (Images copyright Andreas Tolias Lab, Baylor College of Medicine) About us At the Bernstein Center Tübingen, scientists from various disciplines, including theoretical and experimental neurobiology, machine learning, and medicine, collaborate in order to analyze the basis of inference processes in the brain. In particular, a main research goal is to understand the coordinated interaction of neurons during information processing. Contact office@bccn-tuebingen.de Bernstein Center for Computational Neuroscience Tübingen Imprint Privacy	{neuroscience,obama,scientists,neurobiology,neurorobotics,university,tübingen,faculty,science,college,baylor,medicine,braininitiative,mammalian,tuebingen,research,microscopy,interneuron,axons,axon,bernstein,cortex,master,photon,neurons,office,morphology,consortium,timeline,electron,reconstruction,disciplines,funding,architecture,networks,education,pyramidal,somas,cells,switchboard,brain,copyright,computations,planes,connectivity,circuit,andreas,bethge,tissue,machine,tolias,goal,network,team,intelligence,program,vision,data,events,order}	2024-07-14 16:12:20.813295	{https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/crc-1233-robust-vision,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/microns,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/neurorobotics,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/itn-switchboard,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/research/bmbf-funding-2010-2017,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/education,https://www.bccn-tuebingen.de/