rder to pave the way for new measures in prevention, diagnosis, and treatment. Our research aims to enable earlier diagnosis and better treatment of neurodegenerative diseases like Parkinson’s and Alzheimer’s. Prof. Thomas Gasser Site speaker (acting) at DZNE Tübingen Through human clinical observation and threapy studies, scientists at the DZNE in Tübingen are also working on a better method for early detection of Alzheimer’s, Parkinson’s, and ataxias, and on new therapeutic measures. To this end, they are examining the research participants to find biomarkers, which are measurable biological indicators (in the blood or cerebrospinal fluid, for example) that can be used to detect a disease and assess how it will progress. Clinical research in Tübingen is also dedicated to the rare, hereditary form of Parkinson’s disease. Your commitment can make a big difference! By participating in scientific studies, donating brain tissue or providing financial support, you can make a significant contribution to medical progress and a healthy future. Clinical Trials Unit (CTU) Further information and contact to our study team can be found here . Clinical studies Here you will find a current overview of our clinical studies. Researchers in Tübingen Dr. Vikas Bansal Dr. Vikas Bansal Career Development Fellow Biomedical Data Science Prof. Dr. Thomas Gasser Prof. Dr. Thomas Gasser Head of clinical research Tübingen, Group Leader Parkinson Genetics PD Dr. Christian Johannes Gloeckner PD Dr. Christian Johannes Gloeckner Group Leader Functional Neuroproteomics and Translational Biomarkers in Neurodegenerative Diseases Dr. Stefan Hauser Dr. Stefan Hauser Group Leader Advanced cellular models of neurodegeneration Prof. Dr. Mathias Jucker Prof. Dr. Mathias Jucker Group Leader Cell Biology of Neurological Diseases Dr. Deborah Kronenberg-Versteeg Dr. Deborah Kronenberg-Versteeg Group leader Glial Cell Biology N. N. N. N. Genome Biology of Neurodegenerative Diseases N. N. N. N. Applied Genomi